report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 45-year-old, uncooperative male with a witnessed tonic-clonic seizure, postictal confusion, agitation, and possible withdrawal symptoms.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Librium, Haldol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake record in a patient who becomes cooperative over the course of the study.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is low voltage, well organized with a symmetric, reactive posterior rhythm of approximately 10 Hz.  There is generous background beta activity.  Brief drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the posterior dominant rhythm with an increase in beta activity.
HR:  116 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The beta activity described above may be due to this patient’s medications.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat tracing in the lab with sleep and hyperventilation could be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is an 56-year-old gentleman with a hip fracture, alcohol abuse, epilepsy, and a DVT.  The patient had three seizures on 2/5/03.  He requires restraints for self-induced picking at his skin.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Topamax, antibiotics, many others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is diffusely slow and poorly organized with a low voltage delta and theta frequency activity. This pattern is seen when the patient is awake or stuporous.  The patient is observed by a nurse and tech and there is IV or other drip.  There was an unusual, somewhat periodic complex identified in the background with an unusual field of spread and phase reversal.  In specific montages including a referential ear montage, the activity is clearly maximum on the right but with spread to the left and in some montages which accentuate P4, it is possible to identify a P4 phase reversal.  The activity is usually unilateral but sometimes bilateral and sometimes seems to be asynchronous on the other side.  Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in faster frequency activity, as well as brief arousals.
The unusual, periodic activity in this record can be clearly differentiated from EKG artifact and there is no identifiable other source of artifact for this individual.
HR:  104 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Periodic activity poorly localized but probably maximum in the right parietal region, although sometimes generalized.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing differs from previous studies and suggests a process in the parietal regions, which may be epileptiform in nature.  No seizures were recorded.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing. Periodic activity poorly localized but probably maximum in the right parietal region, although sometimes generalized.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 9-year-old, right-handed male with staring spells, attention deficit disorder, mild cerebral palsy, developmental delay with delayed walking at age three.  Breach delivery, anxiety, hyperactivity, and asthma.
MEDICATIONS: Celexa.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized for a child of this age with a 10.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with 50 to 70 V and age-appropriate quantities of background theta activity.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing an increase in theta with one or two shifting asymmetries but no definite lateralization.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in amplitude of the alpha rhythm with an increase in background theta.  Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.
Photic stimulation elicits driving at 5 Hz and faster flash frequencies.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG is within the range of normal for a child of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record and no significant lateralizing features were seen. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat tracing may be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG is within the range of normal for a child of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 3.1-year-old male with a history of syncope, cyanosis treated with ice.  More than one episode of loss of consciousness.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the Pediatric Unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the child is awake. In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized for a child of this age with an 8.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm reaching 100 V and some posterior slow waves of youth.  An attempt is made with hyperventilation and there is some background slowing identified with hyperventilation, although the full three minutes could not be completed.  LAMBDA was seen in portions of the record.  Very brief drowsiness is characterized by a small amount of background slowing.
HR:  132 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG for a child of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The normal developmental milestones have been achieved.  No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy and clinical correlation is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG for a child of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is an 83-year-old woman with right-sided weakness, confusion, aphasia, found with a bruise over the eye, extended her stroke this morning.
MEDICATIONS: Labetalol, insulin, others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is awake and apprehensive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Much of the EEG is obscured by the patient’s muscle artifact.  She is biting or grinding her jaw throughout much of the record. Interpretable portions of the record show a pattern, which appears to be relatively symmetric with a mixture of rhythmic theta and delta activity, with a primary frequency of rhythmic theta.  There are no significant asymmetries, although the muscle artifact may obscure such.
HR:  116 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Because of the muscle artifact described above, a follow-up study when the patient is a bit calmer may be helpful to identify underlying focal features.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 23-year-old male with MVA, multiple injuries, head injury requiring treatment with Dilantin.  Admitted with right flank pain, fever, rash, and acute renal failure.
MEDICATIONS: Percocet, Dilaudid, Tylenol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is primarily a drowsy record. Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is symmetric. The vast majority of the record is drowsiness with rhythmic background theta.  Symmetric vertex waves are identified in stage I sleep.
Brief awake state is characterized by an 8.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Photic stimulation does not significantly activate the record.
HR:  88 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG at the limits of normal primarily in drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The excessive drowsiness may be due to this patient’s medications.  A follow-up EEG in the lab when the patient is more alert may be helpful in determining whether or not there is an underlying epileptic focus in this individual with head trauma.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG at the limits of normal primarily in drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 20-year-old male found unresponsive with a blood alcohol level of 375.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz, 40 V posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Occasional posterior slow waves of youth are identified, as is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record, increasing the amplitude of the background.  Immediately after HV, the patient becomes somewhat drowsy with slow rolling eye movements followed by attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in background theta.  Vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles are seen in stage II sleep.
Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If clinically indicated, a repeat tracing capturing deeper stages of sleep could be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 76-year-old gentleman with hypoglycemic attack, left leg shaking, and chronic ischemic white matter disease seen on MRI.
MEDICATIONS: Coumadin, insulin, Lipitor, and Atenolol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record without hyperventilation or photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized for a subject of this age with a 9 Hz, 40 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements. Vertex waves are seen in stage I sleep. There are also some bursts of frontally predominant delta in the transition from wakefulness to sleep.
HR:  66 BPM, irregular.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness for a subject of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness for a subject of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 67-year-old gentleman who had missed dialysis and had a prolonged seizure in dialysis.  The patient received IV Dilantin and developed chorea movements immediately afterwards.  History of right cerebellar infarct.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the patient is having continuous chorea form movements. These movements partly obscure the EEG.  There does not appear to be an underlying epileptiform correlate with the movements, however.  As the EEG continues, approximately six minutes into the EEG, the movements decrease and the EEG pattern is one of diffuse background slowing with poor organization and a mixture of rhythmic delta and theta frequency activity.  There are occasional shifting asymmetries and occasionally there is higher amplitude frontally predominant delta in one hemisphere or the other.
As the recording continues and the patient is moving less, there is an area of focal delta identified from the left occipital/posterior temporal region.
HR:  104 BPM, irregular.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing and poor organization.
Occasional focal slowing identified at the close of the record characterized by a left occipital temporal delta.
Choreiform movements without EEG change.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: As discussed with the clinical team, the chorea form movements may be an adverse effect of Phenytoin infusion and did not appear to be seizures.  A follow-up EEG may be of use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing and poor organization. Occasional focal slowing identified at the close of the record characterized by a left occipital temporal delta. Choreiform movements without EEG change.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 57-year-old male with alcohol withdrawal seizures, chronic cerebrovascular disease, and pneumonia.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Hydralazine, Labetalol, Catapres, others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. It was felt that the patient was hyperventilating throughout the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the EEG begins, the patient is awake in a noisy bedside environment with a number of background conversations that appear not to be related to him or his care.  He is markedly tachypneic. The background EEG demonstrates an awake pattern with an 8.5 Hz, 30 to 50 V posterior dominant rhythm in a background with generous amounts of beta activity.  There is a fair amount of movement artifact, but there is no definite background slowing. Photic stimulation elicits driving at intermediate and faster flash frequencies.
HR:  140 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The clinical team was contacted regarding the tachypnea and tachycardia.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 65-year-old male with Dilantin toxicity, multi-infarct dementia, alcohol abuse, and lead poisoning.
MEDICATIONS: Lipitor, Zonisamide, Paxil, Dilantin, others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is somnolent with nonsensical speech.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is diffusely slow.  There is shifting asymmetries and some portions of the record demonstrate relative suppression on the right compared to the left. The overall background is one of theta frequency activity with occasional delta and occasional faster frequency activity.  There is no well-defined posterior dominant rhythm in apparent wakefulness.  There is a discrete sharp and slow complex identified in the left central parietal region, seen particularly in drowsiness.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Intermittent suppression from the right.
Left central parietal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No seizures were recorded.  This EEG supports a diffuse disorder of cerebral function effecting both gray and white matter, which may include toxic and/or metabolic encephalopathy or postictal state.  A partial mechanism for epilepsy can be considered.  Correlation with imaging is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing. Intermittent suppression from the right. Left central parietal sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 14-year-old male with multiple craniospinal surgeries, learning disabled with breakthrough seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Valproate, Lamotrigine, Dopamine, and sedative hypnotics.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The child is intubated and has a previous craniotomy scar.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is abnormal and is at times discontinuous.  The overall pattern is one of delta with occasional bursts of frontally predominant fast activity including a mixture of beta, as well as sharply contoured theta frequency activity.  The record is intermittently discontinuous.  There is an amplitude asymmetry with higher amplitude fast activity on the right.  There are occasional bursts of sharply contoured delta activity from the right temporal region.  Stimulation of the patient is associated with less in the way of discontinuity, but not a significant alerting response.
HR:  104 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing with a discontinuous pattern.
Intermittent bursts of fast activity, higher amplitude on the right compared to the left.
Occasional sharply contoured delta from the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a severe, diffuse disorder of cerebral function effecting both hemispheres, perhaps the right more than the left.  Because of the intermittent discontinuity and the history of sedation, the possibility of either administration of anesthetic doses of sedatives, hypnotic medications, or a severe disorder of cerebral function could be considered. No seizures were recorded.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing with a discontinuous pattern. Intermittent bursts of fast activity, higher amplitude on the right compared to the left. Occasional sharply contoured delta from the right.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 74-year-old woman with dementia and abnormal MRI. She also had recurrent loss of consciousness and sphenoid/orbital abnormality on MRI.
MEDICATIONS: Heparin, Metoprolol, others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record. The tech has some problems with the T2 electrode.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is low voltage.  There is a low voltage, posterior dominant rhythm identified of approximately 9.5 Hz, with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by symmetric background theta, attenuation of the alpha, and an increase in background beta. In the transition to and from stage I sleep, there are rare occasional bursts of shifting asymmetries.  The patient is noted to have some eye movement in sleep.  POSTS, vertex waves, and K complexes are seen in stage II sleep.
HR:  82 BPM, slightly irregular.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for a subject of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No definite focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are an important consideration, a repeat tracing could be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for a subject of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 56-year-old male found unresponsive at home with rising temperature, CPK, and multiple metabolic abnormalities.
MEDICATIONS: Ceftriaxone, Erythromycin, Fentanyl, and Versed (these were stopped one hour prior to the EEG).
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is comatose and unresponsive. (intubated ?).  check tech sheet
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is medium to low amplitude and is comprised of a pattern that is a mixture of rhythmic 4 to 6 Hz theta frequency activity, which occurs in bursts with slower underlying low voltage delta activity in a somewhat discontinuous or paroxysmal pattern. The theta activity is most prominent in the frontal regions where it is sometimes higher amplitude and more sharply contoured and may reach a frequency of 7 to 8 Hz, with a 7 to 8 Hz discharge among the theta frequency activity.  Stimulation of the patient does not significantly activate the record.
HR:  142 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Replacement of normal background with a pattern of rhythmic theta, smaller amounts of delta, and subtle discontinuity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These features are non-specific, but support a diffuse disorder of cerebral function.  The pattern would be typical of that of pharmacologic coma. No definite focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record. If additional information is required, a repeat tracing after this patient’s sedative, hypnotic medications have worn off may be of use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Replacement of normal background with a pattern of rhythmic theta, smaller amounts of delta, and subtle discontinuity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 53-year-old woman with an episode of aphasia, a right central facial, and a question of a tumor versus stroke identified on MRI.
MEDICATIONS: Coumadin, Digoxin, others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the or at the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is low voltage and rich in beta frequency activity.  There is a 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm identified from the right occipital region.  The primary pattern is a drowsy pattern, but in drowsiness there is sharply contoured theta frequency activity maximum at F7.  In addition, there seems to be a slight variability and at times there is a bit more theta frequency in the right frontal region compared to the left, although the central regions are symmetric.  As the patient continues in a relatively drowsy state, there is persistent rhythmic theta identified from the left frontotemporal region with left frontal sharp and slow wave complexes.  These are discrete and are best identified with a sensitivity of 5.  They can be identified both in the montages which accentuate temporal abnormalities, as well as referential montages. Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.
HR:  98 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness due to:
Subtle focal slowing from the left anterior temporal region with associated discrete sharp waves and sharply contoured delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a structural abnormality in the left frontotemporal region and raises the possibility of a partial mechanism for seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness due to Subtle focal slowing from the left anterior temporal region with associated discrete sharp waves and sharply contoured delta.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 30-year-old male with a history of left-sided CVA in January 2002 who presented with a strange feeling and sound in the back of his head like his stomach is growling.  Hypertension, Lyme disease, MRI with white matter abnormalities.
MEDICATIONS: check tech sheet
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and a briefly drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 11 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.   Brief drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic background theta.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and does not activate the record. Photic stimulation elicits driving at 7 and 15 Hz as well as faster flash frequencies.
HR:  102 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are an important consideration, a repeat tracing would be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 67-year-old gentleman admitted for CVA and complex partial seizures.  The patient had an episode of a bad smell followed by upper and lower extremity weakness, slurred speech, and near syncope with difficulty walking.  Episode lasted for about five minutes.  History of hypertension, diabetes, DJD, Guillaine-Barre syndrome in the past.  MRI: subacute infarct and new left pontine infarct.
MEDICATIONS: Antihypertensives and aspirin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric and fairly well organized.  There is a 10 Hz, 25 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Sleep is characterized by attenuation of the background with mixed frequency, vertex waves, and a few spindles.  Deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.  There was a single channel artifact at T5 due to head rocking.
HR: 66 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal features or epileptiform discharges were seen in this tracing.  If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG in the lab may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 48-year-old woman with syncope versus seizures with chest pain.
MEDICATIONS: ?
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the ER using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the patient is drowsy.  The background EEG is primarily theta.  There is some temporal wicket activity.  There are intermittent bursts of sharply contoured irregular, higher amplitude theta frequency activity with bursts typically lasting under three seconds in duration.  Most of them last under one second.  Some of these have an underlying spike and slow wave complex seen in association with them.  In addition, unfortunately this is also the region where the patient has EKG artifact and an irregular heart rate.  The bursts of irregular temporal theta have a left mid-to-anterior temporal underlying spike and slow wave or sharp and slow wave complex.  On occasion, that epileptiform activity isn’t seen in the posterior rather than the anterior temporal region.  In addition, there is a bilateral distribution of the regular theta.
Stimulation of the patient elicits an alerting with a very brief posterior dominant rhythm, which is approximately 7 to 8 Hz.
HR:  96 BPM, irregular.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Irregular, sharply contoured bursts of theta activity with an underlying sharp wave from the left temporal region with variable maximum and occasional bitemporal involvement.
Generalized background slowing.
Irregular heart rate.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The irregular heart rate or the epileptiform activity could account for this patient’s loss of consciousness and clinical correlation may be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Irregular, sharply contoured bursts of theta activity with an underlying sharp wave from the left temporal region with variable maximum and occasional bitemporal involvement. Generalized background slowing. Irregular heart rate.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 59-year-old male with a history of seizures and epilepsy onset since his teenage years. Last seizure was several weeks ago.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol, Dilantin, and Phenobarbital.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the Long-Term EEG Monitoring unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is disorganized and diffusely slow. There is 6 to 7 Hz, 40 to 60 V posterior dominant alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Occasional left temporal sharp activity with focal slowing is observed.  In random sleepiness, during the night sleep stage, left temporal sharp activity was dramatically increased.  Occasional spikes, as well as rare right temporal sharp activity was also observed.    During deeper sleep stages, occasional left sharp activity and rare right temporal sharp activity can be seen.  Sleep is characterized by vertex waves, spindles, and K complexes.  Deeper sleep stages reveal synchronized delta activity with high amplitudes more than 75 V occupying half or more than half of the epoch.
EVENTS:  No seizure events were reported, and no push button events occurred over this long-term EEG monitoring.
HR:  56 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Frequent, left temporal sharp activity with focal slowing.
Occasional right temporal sharp activity.
Long-Term Monitoring, 10/14/03 at 06:34 to 10/15/03 at 01:14
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 59-year-old male with a history of seizures and epilepsy onset since his teenage years. Last seizure was several weeks ago.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and Phenobarbital. Tegretol was discontinued.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the Long-Term EEG Monitoring unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is disorganized and diffusely slow. There is 6 to 7 Hz, 40 to 60 V posterior dominant alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Frequent left temporal sharp activity, sometimes continuous, with focal slowing was observed in wakefulness.  In light sleep, the left temporal sharp activity sometimes appeared with spikes and was continuous with focal slowing.  Occasional independent right temporal sharp activity was also observed. In deeper stages of sleep, the independent temporal sharp activity is also seen.  Sleep is characterized by vertex waves, spindles, K complexes, and high synchronous delta activity.
EVENTS:  No seizures events were recorded, and no push button events occurred over this period of long-term monitoring.
HR:  56 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Disorganized background with diffuse slowing.
Independent temporal sharp activity with frequent left temporal sharp activity which was continuous.
Long-Term Monitoring, 10/15/03 at 06:47  to 10/16/03 at 08:32
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 59-year-old male with a history of seizures and epilepsy onset since his teenage years. Last seizure was several weeks ago.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and Phenobarbital.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the Long-Term EEG Monitoring unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is disorganized and diffusely slow. There is 6 to 7 Hz, 40 to 60 V posterior dominant alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Left temporal sharp activity and occasional left temporal spike waves were observed.  The left sharp activity frequently repeated in runs, with focal slowing.  Occasionally, independent right sharp activity was also observed in the right temporal area.  The left focal features were more dramatic during sleep at night, with slow activity repeatedly appearing. Sleep is characterized by vertex waves, spindles, K complexes, and high synchronous delta activity.
EVENTS:  No seizure activity was recorded, and no push button events occurred during this portion of the record.
HR:  64 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Disorganized background with diffuse slowing.
Frequent sharp or spike waves with slow activity in the left temporal region.
Occasional right temporal sharp activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The focal EEG findings seen in this record may be responsible for the partial mechanism of epilepsy in this patient.  No seizure were recorded over this three-day long-term EEG monitoring.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Frequent, left temporal sharp activity with focal slowing. Occasional right temporal sharp activity. Long-Term Monitoring, 10/14/03 at 06:34 to 10/15/03 at 01:14

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 58-year-old male on an LVAD device with hemorrhagic complications, noted to have intermittent left motor asymmetry and intracerebral hemorrhage on CT scan.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, morphine, Haldol, Fentanyl and many others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is sedated.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The initial portions of the record are low voltage beta with superimposed significant muscle activity.  As the recording continues, the patient becomes less tense and a low voltage beta pattern is identified with symmetric underlying low voltage delta.  Stimulation of the patient clearly produces an alerting with an increase in muscle, as well as the brief appearance of some alpha frequency activity.  There is variability in the record and there are portions of the record where there is lower voltage symmetric theta and delta.  The tech notes that the patient occasionally tenses his hands or bites on his endotracheal tube, again producing an increase in muscle and beta activity.  In later portions of the record, as the patient appears to relax, there is lower voltage, slow delta seen.
HR:  102 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Replacement of normal background with beta frequency pattern.
Generalized background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Some of the features described above are compatible with a pharmacologic coma.  The spontaneous reactivity and variability are positive prognostic signs even in the setting of sedation.  With relaxation, we see a diffuse pattern of delta supporting a diffuse disorder of cerebral function and contributing factors may include the CNS processes described above or the medications.  No focal features and no epileptiform features were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Replacement of normal background with beta frequency pattern. Generalized background slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 54-year-old gentleman with seizures secondary to head trauma in 1989, status-post right craniotomy and removal of a blood clot. Last seizure was eight months ago.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and Phenobarbital.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage I sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is disorganized and the normal posterior alpha rhythm is not seen.  There is diffuse beta fast activity.  There is nearly continuous right temporal focal slowing as well as an occasional breach rhythm identified.  Post-hyperventilation shows frequent right temporal and occasional right central sharp activity as well as a breach rhythm.  Sleep is characterized by vertex waves, but deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.
Photic stimulation elicits mild driving, right more than left. Also sharp activity in the right central area was seen during photic stimulation.
HR:  56 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Disorganized background with right temporal and central sharp activity, as well as a breach rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The breach rhythm is consistent with a craniotomy in this patient.  The focal sharp waves support a  partial mechanism of epilepsy in this patient.  The diffuse beta activity may be secondary to Phenobarbital.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Disorganized background with right temporal and central sharp activity, as well as a breach rhythm.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 4-year-old female with cerebral palsy, epilepsy, born at 42 weeks, but with a perinatal stroke.
MEDICATIONS: Phenobarbital.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The child is described as crying.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: This is an extremely challenging EEG due to muscle and motion artifact, however, in the interpretable portions of the record, the background is diffusely slow with a mixture of beta and theta frequency activity.  The anticipated developmental milestones for a child of this age are not well defined.  There are brief portions of the record when the child awakens with spontaneous eye opening and eye closure.  At this time, there is a suggestion of a 6 Hz posterior dominant rhythm in a background with rhythmic 3 to 4 Hz activity.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is hypersynchronous, high amplitude, frontally predominant delta activity, as well as some rhythmic slowing from the left.  In the brief portions of the record without movement artifact, there appears to be an underlying sharp and slow wave or spike and slow wave focus from the posterior regions.
HR:  140 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for a child of this age due to:
Absence of some of the developmental milestones, as well as appropriate developmental organization.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Because of the amount of artifact, no other inferences should be made from this EEG.  There appears to be underlying epileptiform activity from the right as well as asynchronicity as the child drifts off to sleep.  If further characterization of this child’s epilepsy is important, a repeat, sedated study may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for a child of this age due to Absence of some of the developmental milestones, as well as appropriate developmental organization.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 37-year-old male with a left temporal and occipital hemorrhage.

MEDICATIONS:  Haldol, thiamine folic acid, and antibiotics.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is intubated and sedated with Versed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG is asymmetric and low voltage.  The normal posterior alpha rhythm is barely seen.  There is diffuse beta activity.  There is a nearly continuous left frontal and central slowing with polymorphic and arrhythmic delta activity.  Fast activity on the left anterior was also observed.  Stimulation of the patient did not cause variability.

HR:  114 BPM.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Asymmetric, disorganized and low voltage background.
2. Diffuse beta activity.
3. Focal slowing of polymorphic and arrhythmic delta activity in the left frontal and central areas.
4. Fast activity in the left anterior region.
5. Lack of variability with stimulation.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing demonstrates a severe cerebral dysfunction involving both gray and white matter.  The polymorphic slowing in the left frontal central region is suggestive of an underlying pathological process in this patient.  The diffuse beta activity together with fast activity in the left anterior region, as well as the absence of variability with stimulation, may be secondary to medications such as a pharmacological coma or patient in coma secondary to a structural lesion in the brain involving the reticular formation.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  When the patient is more stabilized or weaned off sedative medications, a follow-up EEG may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Asymmetric, disorganized and low voltage background. 2. Diffuse beta activity. 3. Focal slowing of polymorphic and arrhythmic delta activity in the left frontal and central areas. 4. Fast activity in the left anterior region. 5. Lack of variability with stimulation.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is an 89-year-old woman admitted for change in mental status with acute encephalopathy, agitation, acute renal failure, afib, and small MI with small vessel disease.  This is a follow-up EEG tracing.
MEDICATIONS: Antibiotics and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed. The patient is intubated and ventilator dependent.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is symmetric, continuous, and very low voltage with excessive beta activity.  A few 5 to 6 Hz delta activity is seen in the posterior region.  Stimulation of the patient caused spontaneous movement and increased the theta activity as well as scant amounts of delta activity.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Low voltage, diffusely slow background.
Excessive beta activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing is suggestive of a cerebral dysfunction involving both gray and white matter.  The excessive amount of beta activity may be due to medications such as benzodiazepine use.  The low voltage pattern may be due to the patient’s age and is considered normal for a patient of this advanced age.  In comparison to this patient’s previous EEG of February 19, 2004, as well as the presence of interaction caused by stimulation, this EEG is much improved.  No epileptiform discharges were seen in this tracing.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Low voltage, diffusely slow background. Excessive beta activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 93-year-old male with an episode of tremulousness of the upper extremities and eyes rolling back in the head.  CT demonstrates generalized atrophy.
MEDICATIONS: Aspirin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and asleep record with photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG includes rhythmic 6 to 7 Hz theta activity.  There is a posterior dominant rhythm, which is more on the order of  5 to 6 Hz.  There is occasional, shifting, underlying arrhythmic delta activity. Brief stage I sleep is characterized by vertex waves followed by arousals.  Brief stage II sleep includes vertex waves and spindles.  Stimulation does not elicit a driving response.
HR:  60 BPM, irregular.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing with rhythmic slowing.
Occasional shifting arrhythmic delta activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG remains slow in the context of this patient’s age.  Consideration includes a toxic or metabolic encephalopathy as well as a chronic process including an underlying dementia. No epileptiform features were identified in this record.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing with rhythmic slowing. Occasional shifting arrhythmic delta activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 70-year-old woman admitted with hallucinosis, right PCA and MCA infarcts with left hemiparesis, fluctuating mental status, and Alzheimer’s disease.
MEDICATIONS: Plavix and Nifedipine.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and briefly drowsy record in a patient with nearly continuous oral facial dyskinesias.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is nearly obscured by muscle, but underlying the muscle the activity appears to be of low voltage and relatively continuous.  As the patient drifts off to sleep, there is less in the way of background muscle and the EEG is a mixture of alpha and theta frequency activity.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is an intrahemispheric asymmetry apparent.  There is a posterior dominant rhythm identified of approximately 7 Hz on the left, but the faster frequency activity from the right hemisphere appears to be relatively attenuated.  As the patient becomes more responsive, again the oral facial dyskinesias and the prominent muscle activity obscure the EEG.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Modest background slowing.
Intrahemispheric asymmetry with disruption of faster frequency activity from the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a structural abnormality on the right involving gray matter, as well as at least a mild, diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Modest background slowing. Intrahemispheric asymmetry with disruption of faster frequency activity from the right.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 68-year-old woman with an anoxic/hypoglycemic episode in the field, acute renal failure, prior left MCA stroke with chronic hemiparesis and aphasia, now persistently unresponsive.
MEDICATIONS: Valproate, Vancomycin, and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is unresponsive with occasional eye movement or facial grimacing and unilateral deviation of the right eye (left eye prosthetic).
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is markedly abnormal.  The activity from the left hemisphere is relatively suppressed with occasional left mid-to-posterior temporal sharp waves.  The right hemisphere demonstrates essentially a theta pattern.  There are occasional frontal sharp waves, left greater than right, some of which have a periodic nature to them.  Stimulation of the patient does not significantly active the record.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Intrahemispheric asymmetry, slower on the left than the right.
Left mid-temporal sharp waves.
Right frontal or bilateral periodic complexes.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a severe, diffuse disorder of cerebral function.  Processes involving each hemisphere should be considered.  Correlation with follow-up neuroimaging may be helpful.  No seizures were recorded.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Intrahemispheric asymmetry, slower on the left than the right. Left mid-temporal sharp waves. Right frontal or bilateral periodic complexes.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 58-year-old woman with a history of syncope versus seizure 12/03/03, lower extremity weakness, and liver transplant in 1995.
MEDICATIONS: Prograf, Coumadin, and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 11 Hz, 40 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements and a more diffuse distribution of the beta frequency activity.  Abundant vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS are seen in stage II sleep.
Hyperventilation is performed with good effort producing a small amount of background theta.  Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 63-year-old woman with change in mental status, multiple strokes, HTN, and CABG.
MEDICATIONS: Digoxin, Coumadin, Benadryl, and others.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Generalized background slowing and poor organization.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There were no significant focal or epileptiform features identified in this record.  The features described above are non-specific and may be seen in a chronic or acute disturbance of cerebral function.  There are no specific hallmarks of a metabolic encephalopathy although a metabolic encephalopathy may produce a similar pattern.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Generalized background slowing and poor organization.

report:

report:

report:

report:
HISTORY: This is a 28-year-old woman with seizures since age 11.  She also has some unusual facial features.
MEDICATIONS: Paxil, Ranitidine, Seroquel, Lasix, Cozaar, and Albuterol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.

There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation increases the amplitude of the background. Photic stimulation elicits driving.
HR:  78 BPM.

Sharp activity observed in the left frontal and temporal areas.
Bursts of left temporal slowing with sharp and slow wave complexes in the left temporal area.

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Sharp activity observed in the left frontal and temporal areas. Bursts of left temporal slowing with sharp and slow wave complexes in the left temporal area.

report:

HR:  120 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in sleep.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 26-year-old woman with seizures versus syncope, feels hot and then passes out.

The patient drifts in and out of stage II sleep with prominent vertex waves, POSTS, and spindles.

report:

report:
HISTORY: 53-year-old woman with a history of stroke now with right sided shaking with numbness.
MEDICATIONS: Celebrex, ASA, Lipitor, Elavil, and asthma medication.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric and fairly well organized for age.  There is a 10 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm, which is well attenuated with eyes closed.  There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  In the beginning of the record, rhythmic mid-temporal theta is seen.  Occasional left temporal focal slowing is also noted.  Hyperventilation did not activate the record.  Drowsiness is characterized by a mixed frequency of activity, but deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.
Photic stimulation elicits driving.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness due to:
1.	Occasional left temporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Rhythmic mid temporal theta activity is also know as psychomotor variant and can be seen in individuals of this age.  The left temporal focal slowing is suggestive of an underlying pathological process.  No epileptiform activity was recorded in this tracing.  If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG capturing deeper stages of sleep or sleep deprivation prior to the EEG may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness due to 1.Occasional left temporal focal slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 46-year-old, right-handed male who had an episode on Memorial Day.  Legs went numb.  The patient began spinning around and then had loss of consciousness, falling to the grass.  MRI demonstrated right temporal hematoma plus other areas of hemorrhage, thought to be older than the date of injury.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Lisinopril, and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and briefly drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz, 30 to 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a MU rhythm identified from the central regions, although testing is not performed. The most notable abnormality in this record is identified in wakefulness, augmented slightly in hyperventilation and includes rhythmic theta frequency activity from the right mid-temporal region.  In hyperventilation, some of this focal slowing becomes less rhythmic and slows to arrhythmic, 1.5 to 2 Hz. Brief  drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background beta activity.  Although the background is somewhat sharply contoured, there is no definite epileptiform activity in the region of the focal slowing.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous bilateral driving.
HR:  80 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing with disruption of faster frequency activity and rhythmic theta and arrhythmic delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a structural abnormality affecting both gray and white matter.  No definite epileptiform features were seen.  If indicated, a follow-up study may be of use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Focal slowing with disruption of faster frequency activity and rhythmic theta and arrhythmic delta.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is an 11-year-old female with epilepsy since age 3; last seizure two years ago with shaking, drooling, and incontinence.  Positive family history of epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized for a child of this age with a 10 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Noted in wakefulness and increasing in drowsiness is a right central spike and slow wave complex with a large field of spread.  This ranges from discrete to a high amplitude complex and at times the field of spread varies from central parietal to frontocentral.  It may occur as couplets or a brief run of epileptiform activity and does appear to be associated with underlying focal slowing in the central parietal region.  Photic stimulation elicits a scant driving response bilaterally.  The epileptiform activity can be seen on one occasion during photic stimulation, but is not augmented by photic. Hyperventilation elicits a small amount of theta in the background.  Following this, drowsiness is characterized by a small amount of generalized background slowing.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Right central spike and slow wave activity with occasional brief bursts of spike and slow wave activity.
Subtle underlying focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a localization-related mechanism for epilepsy.  Because of the concomitant focal slowing, consideration for an underlying structural or functional abnormality rather than a benign localization-related epilepsy is appropriate, although this may still represent a somewhat unusual benign localization-related epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Right central spike and slow wave activity with occasional brief bursts of spike and slow wave activity. Subtle underlying focal slowing.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 48-year-old male with three seizures in his 20s, recent epidural hematoma with subsequent seizure characterized by a strange feeling, as if he is about to pass out, jerking, and then a tonic-clonic seizure with incontinence.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 55-year-old male with a right thalamic plate with intraventricular hemorrhage and placement of a right ventriculostomy.  Twitching of the face two days ago, right downward gaze deviation last night, and right-sided twitching today.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Phenobarbital, and Ativan.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is intubated and poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is markedly abnormal and includes a subtle, discontinuous pattern.  When there is activity identified, the activity is mixed frequency, low voltage, with alpha and theta frequency activity as well as smaller amounts of delta.  The periods with activity range from 3 to 7 seconds in duration and the periods of suppression averages approximately 5 seconds in duration.  There is some variability towards the close of the record.  The periods with activity are a little bit longer lasting than those in the initial portions of the record and there is some higher amplitude theta there.  Stimulation of the patient does not clearly activate the record, although stimulation was performed primarily at the close of the record as the discontinuity is improving.  There are a few shifting asymmetries more prominent at the end of the record.  There is also a breach rhythm a bit more prominent towards the close of the record.  A single F3 sharp wave is identified.
HR:  92 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Initial burst suppression pattern, which gradually improves as the recording continues.
Some shifting asymmetries with a breach rhythm.  Some portions of the record demonstrate a breach rhythm on the right with a bit more slower frequency activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a severe disturbance of cerebral function.  The improvement over the course of a brief EEG may be due to either improvement in this patient’s neurologic status, or the duration of time since his Phenobarbital infusion.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Initial burst suppression pattern, which gradually improves as the recording continues. Some shifting asymmetries with a breach rhythm.  Some portions of the record demonstrate a breach rhythm on the right with a bit more slower frequency activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 72-year-old woman with left IVH, lumbar drain, seizure today characterized by foaming of the mouth, eyes rolling back, head rocking, irregular  respirations, and ventricular tachycardia requiring intubation and Ativan.

MEDICATIONS: Zoloft, Ativan, and others.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is a relatively immediate postictal study.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is low voltage, relatively featureless with slow, low voltage delta, smaller amounts of theta frequency activity, muscle, and a fair amount of beta. Stimulation of the patient produces a small amount of theta frequency activity.  Towards the close of the record, there is a small increase in background theta.  At the very close of the record, rare, high amplitude right frontal sharp waves are seen.  At the close of the record, occasional high amplitude right frontal sharp waves, as well as bursts of sharply contoured delta are identified.

HR:  __ BPM. CHECK PRELIM SHEET

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Replacement of normal background with severe generalized slowing.
2. High amplitude right frontal sharp waves and associated focal slowing, which crescendo at the end of the EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a severe, diffuse disturbance of cerebral function affecting both gray and white matter.  The beta may be due to medications.  The presence of the right frontal sharp waves really just at the close of the record with at times an almost periodic nature suggests an acute, postictal pattern and an additional EEG recording may be useful in order to make sure that additional seizures do not recur.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Replacement of normal background with severe generalized slowing. 2. High amplitude right frontal sharp waves and associated focal slowing, which crescendo at the end of the EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 72-year-old woman with high-grade carotid stenosis; pre-op EEG.
MEDICATIONS: Heparin, Metformin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  There are intermittent bursts of focal slowing from the left hemisphere, maximum in the centrotemporal and posterior temporal regions.  Mixed with these bursts are occasional sharp waves identifiable at C3, T3, and T5.
Photic stimulation does not significantly activate the record, but there is a prominent burst, nearly 20 seconds long, of rhythmic theta from the left hemisphere, particularly from the centrotemporal regions.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Prominent focal slowing from the left hemisphere, particularly in the centrotemporal region.
Rhythmic theta with superimposed sharp waves and on one occasion with build-up of the theta frequency activity but without true evolution.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a partial mechanism for epilepsy, as well as an irritative cortex.  Additional evaluation of this patient for seizures is appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Prominent focal slowing from the left hemisphere, particularly in the centrotemporal region. Rhythmic theta with superimposed sharp waves and on one occasion with build-up of the theta frequency activity but without true evolution.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 45-year-old woman with multiple medical problems, increasing seizures, migraine headaches, Gilbert’s disease, and problems with crying, mumbling, and change in mental status.
MEDICATIONS: Topamax, Carbamazepine, and many others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record. No previous EEGs were available for comparison.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG demonstrates a 9.5 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm in a record rich in low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  When not stimulated, the patient drifts off to sleep with slow rolling eye movements, attenuation of the alpha rhythm, and an increase in background beta.  There had been crying earlier and the patient seems to have calmed down as she drifts off to sleep.  Brief stage I sleep is characterized by vertex waves.  At 15:37, the tech notes that the patient is not responding.
PHOTIC STIMULATION: The tech attempts to awaken the patient for additional testing.  The EEG shows a slightly awake or drowsy pattern, but the tech notes that the patient is not responding to verbal stimuli.  Photic stimulation continues.  The patient is awake at this time, and a driving response is identified.  In between the driving intervals, a well-defined alpha rhythm can be seen.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage I sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  It is not clear why the patient was not responding to the technologist’s commands.  She remained motionless and consideration for either excessive drowsiness or an emotional reaction may be appropriate. The background beta may be due to this patient’s medicines.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage I sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 91-year-old woman with a pacemaker, diabetes, hypertension, and a fall suffering a subdural hematoma.
MEDICATIONS: Antibiotics.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is intubated.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient is somnolent throughout much of the record.  At this time, the EEG is markedly slow with a mixture of delta and smaller amounts of theta.  This poorly formed, periodic complex is seen in the record with a somewhat unusual field of spread picked up in the left frontal and right posterior quadrant.  Stimulation of the patient clearly produces an alerting response with an increase in theta.  In addition, there is also spontaneous arousals with an increase in theta.  Because of the movement artifact, it is difficult to determine if this periodic delta disappears.  It appears to attenuate to some extent with stimulation.
HR:  72 BPM, paced rhythm.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Marked background slowing particularly when the patient is not stimulated.
Poorly formed bilateral periodic complexes with an unusual field of spread without clinical correlate.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a severe disturbance of cerebral function.  In the context of the patient’s age, these changes may be magnified.  No seizures were recorded and there were no prominent epileptiform features.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Marked background slowing particularly when the patient is not stimulated. Poorly formed bilateral periodic complexes with an unusual field of spread without clinical correlate.
