report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  21 year old right handed woman with 2 episodes of loss of consciousness in October 2011.  She stood up, stretched, felt weak/lightheaded, and had motor movements of body with her head folding in.  These symptoms lasted 30 seconds.  She was disoriented afterward.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  This was to have been a sleep-deprived EEG, but it was not.  It is a conventional 20-minute EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz 40 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm.  There is a small amount of low voltage frontocentral beta activity. Hyperventilation was performed early in the record, producing a posterior predominant hyperventilation response.  In addition, there is some sharply contoured activity with a handful of sharp waves in the right centrotemporal and posterior temporal region noted in hyperventilation. HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
A posterior predominant hyperventilation response in an adult of this age.
The appearance of right central and posterior temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  If additional information is needed, a repeat study perhaps with physiological testing may be helpful to more completely understand the spells that this patient has been experiencing.

report:

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG for an adult of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:   61 year old man with history of CAD, CABG in 1995, COPD, hepatitis B virus, bilateral PEs, hypertension, who presents with respiratory failure and altered mental status.
MEDICATIONS:  Zosyn, vancomycin
REASON FOR STUDY:  Altered mental status.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while unresponsive.  No activating procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 6 Hz, which does not appear to be reactive to eye opening.  There is not a normal amount of frontal central beta.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.  No activating procedures were performed.
During the recording the patient is stimulated, but there appears to be no clear change in the record.  At times intermittently there is periods of faster frequencies coming through the background, but this does not appear to be due to stimulation and it just occurs for seconds.  It may represent arousal.  Overall the background is also consistent with some abnormal discharges, which I will discuss in the next paragraph.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-70 mV.  In addition, there is intermittent triphasic waves seen throughout the recording.
There is also some sharply contoured transient that are maximal in the midline prefrontal, as well as vertex region.  However, this has more of a metabolic/triphasic morphology and does not appear to be epileptic.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
generalized slowing and triphasics.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  However, the presence of triphasics suggests a metabolic component to this encephalopathy.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to generalized slowing and triphasics.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 60-year-old gentleman with previous stroke, left-sided weakness with right carotid stenosis for right carotid endarterectomy.
MEDICATIONS:  Aspirin, hydrochlorothiazide.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  There is arrhythmic delta activity noted in the right hemisphere.  This is somewhat sharply contoured at times with a phase reversal at T4 and a field for the right-sided delta which is a bit more posterotemporal.  There is also some occasional arrhythmic delta on the left.
Photic stimulation did not significantly activate the record.
Heart rate 60 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Shifting arrhythmic delta activity most prominent in the right hemisphere.
Some sharply contoured slowing maximum at T4.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG will be used for this patient's carotid endarterectomy baseline.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to Shifting arrhythmic delta activity most prominent in the right hemisphere. Some sharply contoured slowing maximum at T4.

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Change in mental status.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 56-year-old woman found to have confusion, slurring of her words, generalized weakness, and treated for bacterial meningitis as well as possible generalized anoxic/hypoxic injury.
MEDICATIONS:  None mentioned.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while unresponsive.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  Overall, the background is consistent with delta slowing at 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.  At times there is some intermittent intermixed theta frequencies and there are frequent periodic discharges most consistent with anterior predominant symmetric triphasic waves.  The patient was stimulated but there appears to be no clear change or __________ in the EEG.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized slow wave 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
Periodic discharges consistent with anterior predominant symmetric triphasic waves.
Lack of reactivity to stimulation.
Seizures:  None.

Heart rate:  90 with a very elevated ST segment but regular.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to generalized slowing as well as triphasics.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of moderate to severe diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology but the presence of triphasics may suggest the possibility of metabolic encephalopathy although sometimes they can be seen with hypoxic injury.  No seizures were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to generalized slowing as well as triphasics.

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 52-year-old man with history of alcohol abuse with a seizure, last drink 2 weeks ago, hyponatremia, alcohol abuse, seizure, malnutrition, lung nodules, COPD.
MEDICATIONS:  Pantoprazole, heparin, morphine, erythromycin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while lethargic.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  Overall, there is diffuse delta slowing with, at times, intermixed theta and alpha frequencies in the central region.  At times, there is diffuse muscle artifact and variability, but no major improvement in the frequency.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slowing seen intermittently at T4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts at times fairly frequently.
Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-50 microvolts seen continuously throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to right midtemporal focal slowing, as well as generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the right mid temporal region, as well as moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction, both of which are nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures or clear epileptiform activity was seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to right midtemporal focal slowing, as well as generalized slowing.

report:
HISTORY: 77-year-old woman with severe cardiomyopathy, AICD and syncope.
MEDICATIONS:  Metoprolol, midazolam, aspirin and Plavix.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using the standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient demonstrated wakefulness.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  The background EEG is somewhat slow and a bit disorganized, but at times the alpha rhythm reaches 7.3 Hz.  On other occasions, it slows and is more of a 6 Hz pattern with some 2-4 Hz activity in the background.  Slow rolling eye movements were observed.
Sleep was characterized by dropout of the faster alpha and theta frequency activity with more slow delta.
Heart Rate:  126 BPM, occasionally irregular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG for an adult due to modest background slowing and wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This individual clearly demonstrates wakefulness, although the patient is primarily drowsy.  No focal or epileptiform features were noted.  Please contact the lab if we can be of any additional assistance.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG for an adult due to modest background slowing and wakefulness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 70-year-old woman with a change in mental status six days after aortic surgery, right cerebellar encephalomalacia.
MEDICATIONS:  Protonix, Captopril, morphine, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  This is a awake and drowsy record in a confused individual.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not possible.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In apparent wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat disorganized with a posterior dominant rhythm of 7.5 hertz, excess background theta and some shifting arrhythmic delta.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in theta.  As the patient transitions in and out of stage I sleep, more sleep, irregular delta is noted and the vertex waves that were recorded are somewhat broader than usual.  As the patient transitions to deeper Stage I sleep, more conventional-appearing symmetric vertex waves were noted.
Heart rate 66 BPM with frequent PVCs.
IMPRESSION:
Abnormal electroencephalogram due to #1, background slowing and disorganization.
Slowing the alpha rhythm in apparent wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified in this record. The background slowing and disorganization is a nonspecific finding in a subject of this age and can be due to toxic or metabolic encephalopathy or other, modest diffuse bihemispheric brain process. There were no specific hallmarks of a metabolic encephalopathy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION Abnormal electroencephalogram due to #1, background slowing and disorganization. Slowing the alpha rhythm in apparent wakefulness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 52-year-old male with posttraumatic epilepsy.  The patient was in a recent MVA.  Was a restrained passenger when airbags deployed, and had a tonic-clonic seizure at the scene with recurrent seizure in the field.
MEDICATIONS:  __________ , Ativan, Seroquel.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  This patient was quite somnolent.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing begins, the patient is very sleepy.  The overall pattern is low voltage, a little bit lower voltage on the right than the left (there is no mention of a __________ defect).  The patient transitions in and out of stage II sleep with spindles and K complexes.  There are some bursts of sharply contoured slowing with some arrhythmic delta activity in the left hemisphere, particularly mid temporal region.
As the recording continues, the technologist is able to alert the patient, who demonstrates a 7.5 Hematochezia alpha rhythm.  In the transition in and out of sleep, there are some bursts of sharply contoured delta which are relatively subtle in the left hemisphere, including mid temporal or central temporal region.
Photic stimulation is performed while the patient was relatively drowsy, and did not activate the record.
Heart rate 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
An amplitude asymmetry with a lower voltage record on the right compared to the left.
Background slowing in apparent wakefulness.
Rare bursts of sharply contoured slowing from the left hemisphere.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings may be correlated with imaging.  The amplitude asymmetry may reflect previous CNS injury or changes in the thickness in the patient's skull.  The sharply contoured slowing on the left may be correlated with underlying changes in the left hemisphere.  Hypersomnolence noted may be due to postictal state or medications.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to An amplitude asymmetry with a lower voltage record on the right compared to the left. Background slowing in apparent wakefulness. Rare bursts of sharply contoured slowing from the left hemisphere.

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Episodes of blacking out.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 43-year-old female with episodes of blacking out for 2 years and 1 episode 21 years ago, now with headaches in the frontal region.
PAST MEDICAL HISTORY:  Hypertension and asthma.
MEDICATIONS:  Hydrochlorothiazide, albuterol, Cymbalta, losartan.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures included  hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Continuous T4 electrode artifact throughout the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures produced no abnormal discharges.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
SEIZURES:  None.
HEART RATE:  66.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and drowsy EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Normal awake and drowsy EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and drowsy EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 65-year-old woman, found down with transient left hemiparesis, transient hypoglycemia and transient hypotension, now more awake and alert. Still intubated. CT scan negative for stroke.
MEDICATIONS:  Aspirin, many others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was intubated and somewhat agitated.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This is a technically challenging EEG.  There was significant muscle and motion artifact in an otherwise low-voltage pattern.  On rare occasion, there was a glimpse of an alpha rhythm and when the muscle artifact drops out, there is significant beta.  Toward the close of the record, there is a decrease in muscle artifact, and there is a suggestion of asymmetry with perhaps a bit more delta in the right central region than the left.
Heart rate is 110 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is a technically challenging but abnormal EEG due to:
Replacement of normal background with a low-voltage primarily beta pattern.
A question of a subtle asymmetry in the right hemisphere.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified; however, there is a challenging EEG because of the degree of muscle artifact.  A followup study in the lab, after the patient has been extubated and is cooperative, is suggested if there is concern regarding seizures.  There is questionable slowing on the right which may be correlated with additional imaging.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a technically challenging but abnormal EEG due to Replacement of normal background with a low-voltage primarily beta pattern. A question of a subtle asymmetry in the right hemisphere.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  An 84-year-old male with past stroke, hypertension, diabetes.  The patient reports that he has had multiple episodes that he describes as sugar attacks.  Had an episode leaving church which he described as a presyncopal event but which bystanders noted was associated with post event confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Lovenox, insulin, Norvasc.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  In stage 2 sleep vertex waves, K complexes, spindles and posts were noted.
Notable in this record were intermittent bursts of somewhat rhythmic 3-4 Hz delta activity.  Some of the bursts were sustained.  A handful of these are sharply contoured but without a definitive sharp and slow wave complex.  Wicket was also noted in relaxed wakefulness.
Heart rate 72 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Rhythmic, left temporal focal slowing.
Sharply contoured left temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No definitive sharp waves were seen although there was some sharply contoured slowing.  This EEG supports a structural functional abnormality on the left and may be correlated with imaging.  It is a pattern that is not atypical for epilepsy but this individual does have a previous left frontal infarct.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Rhythmic, left temporal focal slowing. Sharply contoured left temporal slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 67-year-old female with history of epilepsy and depression who presents for followup.  Her last seizure was more than 2 years ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin and Seroquel.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm was 9-9.5 Hz in frequency seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is 7-7.5 Hz diffuse theta activity seen during wakefulness, which is distributed symmetrically.  There is presence of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Drowsiness was characterized by disappearance of the posterior dominant rhythm and slowing of the background and absence of muscle and eye blink artifacts.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and did not result in a driving response.  Heart rate was 70 beats per minute with arrhythmia.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording due to diffuse slowing of the background with theta activity seen during wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings could be due to toxic, metabolic, hypoxic, or infectious encephalopathy.  Alternatively, it could be due to the effect of sedating medications or bilateral cerebral dysfunction or degenerative brain disease.  The general clinical correlation was recommended.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures are identified in this record.  Note that the patient has arrhythmia.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording due to diffuse slowing of the background with theta activity seen during wakefulness.

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Left arm shaking without change in mental status.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 72-year-old lady with a past medical history of breast cancer, atrial fibrillation, hypertension, and right-sided craniectomy for a right parietal lesion, postoperative day #7, had an episode of left arm shaking for 20 seconds without change in mental status.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, digoxin, baclofen, spironolactone, Neurontin, dexamethasone.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement and one-channel EKG.  Wakefulness and sleep were captured.  Activation procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Intermittent F3 electrode artifact was noted.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the posterior dominant rhythm, at best, reaches a frequency of 8.5 Hz with an amplitude of 30 to 50 microvolts, briefly; however, there is excess theta noted throughout the recording.  No normal frontocentral beta activity was noted.
Stage I and stage II sleep was captured.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
Abnormal discharges:
Continuous C4/T4 slowing in the 2 to 4 Hz frequency and 20 to 40 microvolt amplitude range with an additional increased amplitude and frequency which is indicative of breach in that region.
Intermittent independent T3 slowing.
Excess theta in wakefulness.
Seizures:  None.
Heart rate:  54 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Continuous right centrotemporal slowing.
Intermittent independent left mid-temporal slowing.
Excess theta in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is suggestive of focal cerebral dysfunction in the right central region, which is consistent with the patient's known history of tumor and surgery in that region.  In addition, there is focal cerebral dysfunction in the left midtemporal region, which is nonspecific in etiology.  There is also diffuse cerebral dysfunction due to theta range slowing in wakefulness, which is also nonspecific in etiology.  Clinical correlation is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to Continuous right centrotemporal slowing. Intermittent independent left mid-temporal slowing. Excess theta in wakefulness.

report:
LENGTH OF RECORDING:  Approximately 1 hour.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 37-year-old woman with a past medical history of seizures, hepatitis C, asthma, bipolar disorder as well as schizophrenia who now presents for a follow-up EEG.  Last seizure was approximately 8 months ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Protonix, Zofran, Carafate, Reglan, Claritin.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consisted of a well-formed and modulated 9.5-10 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eye opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During sleep symmetrical vertex waves, sleep spindles and K complexes are captured.  POSTS (positive occipital sharp transients of sleep) are noted as well.  Intermittent polymorphic theta activity at high amplitudes is noted over the left temporal region.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and does not result in significant changes in the background.  Stepped photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.
FINDINGS:
Intermittent mild left temporal slowing.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake and asleep 1 hour EEG due to intermittent mild left temporal slowing.  This finding indicates focal cerebral dysfunction, possibly structural in etiology.  The lack of epileptiform discharges in the routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake and asleep 1 hour EEG due to intermittent mild left temporal slowing.  This finding indicates focal cerebral dysfunction, possibly structural in etiology.  The lack of epileptiform discharges in the routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 41-year-old male who developed ineffective endocarditis after multiple dental extractions and had a brief episode of change in mental status today.
MEDICATIONS:  Vancomycin, cefuroxime, oxycodone, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  This was a patient in isolation.
TECHNICAL:  There is some muscle artifact.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is diffusely slow.  In wakefulness, there is more of a pattern of rhythmic slowing with an alpha rhythm ranging from 6.5 to 8 Hz.  There are bursts of rhythmic frontal delta and some occasional bursts of shifting asymmetries.  Features of drowsiness including increase in background slowing.  Snore artifact was identified.  Intermittent, paroxysmal bursts was slow, delta were observed.
Two simple morphology left temporal sharp waves were noted.
Heart rate 96 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity (FIRDA).
Occasional shifting slowing.
Two simple sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is most supportive of diffuse disturbance of cerebral function such as toxic or metabolic encephalopathy.  There are minor shifting asymmetries and 2 simple sharp waves.  Correlation with imaging is suggested, but there are no prominent epileptiform features noted.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing. Frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity (FIRDA). Occasional shifting slowing. Two simple sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 58-year-old woman with epilepsy since age 18.  Last grand mal seizure several months ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Unknown
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This was an awake and asleep record.
Technical: There was no mention that this patient had an asymmetric cranium or asymmetric eye movements. There were a number of artifacts noted and there was an unacceptable impedance at SP2. There was also a fair amount of muscle artifact noted in the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat slow and disorganized.  There is an alpha rhythm of 7-8 Hz.
The record can be re-reviewed to eliminate the FP2 artifact but there still appears to be some focal slowing in the right frontal region.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is again an appearance of some arrhythmic delta activity in the right hemisphere, a bit more prominent in the right frontal area.
Photic stimulation did not significantly activate the record.
Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude in the background.
Heart rate 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized slow and disorganized record.
Question right frontal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Given the technical features described above, the focal findings described above are of unclear clinical significance.  A repeat tracing with careful attention to the impedance is appropriate.  In addition, it is possible that this patient has a craniotomy defect which may have contributed to the pattern described above but finding was not recorded in the technical section.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Generalized slow and disorganized record. Question right frontal focal slowing.

report:
LENGTH OF RECORDING:  22 minutes.
CONDITION OF RECORDING:  The recording was performed at the bedside.  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is an 84-year-old woman who is unresponsive after an episode of asystole of unknown duration.
MEDICATIONS:  Current medications include aspirin, atorvastatin, heparin, famotidine.
INTRODUCTION:
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is no posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior to posterior frequency up to gradient.  The background consists of a mixture of polymorphic low to moderate amplitude, beta and delta, 1-2 second periods of background discontinuity and diffuse abundant low to moderate amplitude EMG artifact.  EMG artifact is highest in amplitude over the right frontal and frontocentral electrodes.  According to the EEG technologist, no noticeable twitching/movement was identified.  Video review does not reveal a source of this EMG artifact.  Any epileptiform discharges would be masked by this EMG artifact.  There were no clear electrographic seizures.  A single EKG lead demonstrated a heart rate of fewer than 60 beats a minute up to 2 seconds, this is between some of the QRS complexes.
FINDINGS:
Moderate diffuse slowing.
Periods of discontinuity.
Abundant EMG artifact that would obscure any underlying epileptiform activity.
No clear electrographic seizures.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal 22 minute EEG due to moderate diffuse slowing and periods of discontinuity.  These findings indicate etiologically no specific cerebral dysfunction in this patient, at least partially related to the period of anoxia.
To better assess presence of any epileptiform discharges or ictal activity, a repeat study with administration of a paralytic agent would be of benefit.  These findings were conveyed to the neurology primary team.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal 22 minute EEG due to moderate diffuse slowing and periods of discontinuity.  These findings indicate etiologically no specific cerebral dysfunction in this patient, at least partially related to the period of anoxia

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 73-year-old man with history of seizures with follow-up EEG, and a past medical history of Alzheimer's, alcohol abuse, hypertension and heart surgery.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Aricept, Haldol, lisinopril, Lipitor, metoprolol, aspirin.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Procedures included photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is some frontal central beta.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Procedures included photic stimulation.  No abnormal discharges.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow wave seen at F7/T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-40 microvolts seen frequently throughout the recording.
Seizures - None.
Heart rate 48.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left anterior temporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left anterior temporal region, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left anterior temporal focal slowing.

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 40-year-old man with history of seizures, here for follow up EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.

Activating procedures, including hyperventilation and photic stimulation, produce no abnormal discharges.
Abnormal discharges:  None.
Seizures:  None.
Heart rate:  96.

report:
LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  20 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 32-year-old woman who has cognitive dysfunction and seizures.  The last seizure was approximately 1 month ago.  The seizures are characterized by eye fluttering, __________ and shallow rapid breaths.
MEDICATIONS:  Current medications include Keppra, Zanaflex and loratadine.
CONDITIONING OF RECORDING:  The recording is performed according tot he standard 10-20 system with an additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.   Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed.  This was a technically difficult study since the patient was not cooperative.  Therefore, high impedances were present at the beginning of the recording on several electrodes.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is continuous movement throughout the recording that limits interpretation of the recording.  During several periods of relative calmness the posterior dominant rhythm consists of low to moderate amplitude, polymorphic 10-11 Hz alpha activity.  The anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient is preserved.  No normal sleep architecture is present.  Hyperventilation is not performed.  Step photic stimulation appears to resolve in symmetrical occipital driving at high rate/frequencies.  No obvious electrographic seizures were captured.
FINDINGS:
Technically a limited study due to nearly continuous movement.
No stage II sleep.
No electrographic seizures.
IMPRESSION:  This appears to be a normal 20-minute awake only electroencephalogram.  However, there was a continuous significant movement throughout the study and focal changes and epileptiform discharges might have been missed.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This appears to be a normal 20-minute awake only electroencephalogram.  However, there was a continuous significant movement throughout the study and focal changes and epileptiform discharges might have been missed

report:
EEG LENGTH:  30 minutes
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 34-year-old woman with a history of seizure disorder who now presents with increasing seizure frequency.  Her last seizure occurred approximately two weeks ago.  Her medications include Dilantin, sertraline, venlafaxine and diphenhydramine.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORDING:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated moderate amplitude 10-1/2 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During drowsiness, the amount of diffuse theta and frontal central beta increases.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and produces mild diffuse background slowing as well as brief bursts of moderate to high amplitude diffuse frontally predominant somewhat rhythmic theta activity.  Similar activity is observed post hyperventilation as well as during drowsiness.  Photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.  Bursts of diffuse frontally predominant moderate to high amplitude somewhat rhythmic theta activity are also observed during photic stimulation.
A single EKG lead demonstrates a heart rate that is at times fewer than 60 beats per minute.
FINDINGS:
No stage II sleep.
No clear epileptiform discharges.
Brief bursts of moderate to high amplitude diffuse frontally predominant theta activity that occur during hyperventilation, post hyperventilation, during drowsiness and during photic stimulation.
IMPRESSION:  This is likely a normal awake and drowsy 30-minute EEG.  Bursts of moderate to high amplitude, somewhat rhythmic theta activity that occur throughout the recording, are of uncertain clinical significance but are not clearly epileptiform.  A repeat longer study with prolonged sleep would be of benefit in this patient.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is likely a normal awake and drowsy 30-minute EEG.  Bursts of moderate to high amplitude, somewhat rhythmic theta activity that occur throughout the recording, are of uncertain clinical significance but are not clearly epileptiform.  A repeat longer study with prolonged sleep would be of benefit in this patient

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 22-year-old male status post anaphylactic injury to shellfish ingestion on the 29th, intubated, multisystem injury, and MI x2.  The patient had seizure-like activity on presentation on the 29th.
MEDICATIONS:  Midazolam and propofol.  Previously treated with Decadron fentanyl and Ativan.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient was comatose, unresponsive and was examined during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly abnormal.  The overall pattern is one of diffuse delta with slow delta and bursts of frontally predominant delta.  In addition, there is prominent beta noted in the background.  The patient was examined on 2 occasions.  On 1 occasion, there was a subtle increase in rhythmic delta which is a little bit faster, trending more towards 3 Hz was noted when the patient was  unstimulated.  Tactile stimulation at the very end of the EEG also produced a little bit of reactivity.
Heart rate 102 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Marked background slowing.
Absence of the normal wave forms.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Although reactivity to external stimuli was subtle it was present and this is a positive prognostic factor.  Of note, this patient's sedative hypnotic medications can play a role in the pattern described above.
__________________________

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 58-year-old male with lifelong epilepsy, tonic-clonic seizures, a seizure 4 days ago out of sleep.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin and phenobarbital, previously Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is a greater than 20 minute, technically satisfactory EEG aside from T1-T2 impedances which were slightly greater than 5 kilohms.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 7.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with generous background theta.
The overall, awake background is relatively low voltage.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in rhythmic theta.  Photic stimulation did not significantly activate the record.
Epileptiform discharges:  Notable in this record were left anterior temporal sharp waves, which were relatively rare.  They ranged from a high amplitude 70 microvolt  T1 sharp waves to more discreet left anterior temporal sharp waves with variable maximum.  On 1 occasion, there is a phase reversal in the referential montage between T1 and F7.  One of these discharges also seems to have more of a left frontocentral localization.
Heart rate 60 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Left anterior temporal sharp waves noted in drowsiness.
Excess theta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the 4th EEG for this patient.  Only 1 prior EEG identified the left temporal sharp waves, but prior EEGs did identify the excess background theta.  This EEG supports a localization-related mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to Left anterior temporal sharp waves noted in drowsiness. Excess theta.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 70-year-old woman with recurrent tonic-clonic seizures from 2 o'clock this afternoon, transferred from Episcopal Hospital.  Patient has not returned to baseline mental status, not speaking well, confused, evaluated for subclinical status epilepticus.

MEDICATIONS:  Versed, others, phenytoin.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the neuro ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1-channel EKG.  This is a technically very challenging EEG in an uncooperative patient.  The EEG captures the awake and agitated state.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the initial sections of the record, the patient is awake and moving about.  The overall background is quite disorganized.  Head rocking artifact is noted, but there was also an increase in amplitude in the right scalp electrodes particularly the right temporal regions.  When the patient is a bit more cooperative, is a bit more theta.  The nurses attempt to console the patient with little success.  At some point, there is an increase in beta as the patient's Versed starts to take effect and the patient started snoring.  As she does so, a more restricted area of focal slowing in the right posterior quadrant was noted and there are discernible, right occipitotemporal sharp waves noted.  The sedation does not last long and the patient is quickly agitated again.  The pattern from the left is also disorganized, but lacks the same quantity of arrhythmic delta activity.  The sharp waves are irregular with a variable maximum and can include T4 or O2.

Heart rate N/A.

IMPRESSION:  Technically challenging, but abnormal EEG due to:
1. Sharp waves from the right hemisphere, typically posterior temporal, but not exclusively occipital or posterior temporal, sometimes mid temporal.
2. Arrhythmic delta activity, right posterior quadrant.
3. Background slowing and disorganization from both hemispheres.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No seizures were recorded.  This EEG supports a structural process on the right involving gray and white matter as well as a localization-related mechanism for epilepsy.  Additional recording may be considered if the patient suffers additional seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Technically challenging, but abnormal EEG due to 1. Sharp waves from the right hemisphere, typically posterior temporal, but not exclusively occipital or posterior temporal, sometimes mid temporal. 2. Arrhythmic delta activity, right posterior quadrant. 3. Background slowing and disorganization from both hemispheres.

report:

Modest generalized background slowing.
Superimposed right focal slowing characterized by intermittent disruption of the frequency activity on the right.

report:
:
History:	76 year old woman found unresponsive yesterday.  She was found to have PEA.
Diffuse body jerks were noted this am.
Medications:	Depakote, Propofol at 20, Vecuronium 8 mg total during the study
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Extended, 40-60 min, portable
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, comatose
Description:
There is no PDR and no AP gradient.  The background consists of a mixture of polymorphic
theta<<delta activity and diffuse frontally predominant polyspikes.  As the recording opens,
polyspikes are low in amplitude and infrequent. As the recording progresses,  they gradually
increase in frequency, amplitude and duration.  Clinically, they are associated with diffuse body
jerks.  Four brief (~20 seconds) clinical and electrographic seizures are captured.  Clinically patient
has diffuse body jerks that rapidly evolve into rhythmic clonic movements of upper extremities.
Patient is given vecuronium at the time of the last seizure, so no movement is identified with that
event.  Electrographically, the first 3 seizures are characterized by diffuse EMG artifact. Patient is
paralyzed at the time of the fourth seizure.  That seizure starts with moderate amplitude diffuse
polyspikes that evolve into a mixture of diffuse 8-10 Hz  activity with underriding low amplitude fast
activity.  At the end of the seizures, rhythmic ~ 3 Hz diffuse delta activity is seen accompanied by
the underriding fast activity.  After each seizure, frequency, duration and amplitude of polyspikes
decrease dramatically.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.  There is no change in the background
activity to visual, auditory, tactile, or noxious stimuli.
Summary of Findings:
Seizure, few, ~20 second each, generalized
Polyspikes, abundant diffuse
No reactivity
Diffuse slowing, polymorphic, severe
Interpretation:
This is a very abnormal 1 hour EEG in a comatose patient due to severe diffuse slowing, lack of
reactivity, frequent diffuse epileptiform discharges (clinically associated with generalized body jerks)
and 4 brief generalized seizures. These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicators of marked
diffuse cerebral dysfunction and profound cortical excitability and in a patient with post-anoxic
brain injury indicate low likelihood of full neurological recovery.  These findings were conveyed to
the neurology consult team and to the primary team at the time of the recording.  Patient will be
placed on a long-term EEG monitoring.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a very abnormal 1 hour EEG in a comatose patient due to severe diffuse slowing, lack of
reactivity, frequent diffuse epileptiform discharges (clinically associated with generalized body jerks)
and 4 brief generalized seizures. These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicators of marked
diffuse cerebral dysfunction and profound cortical excitability and in a patient with post-anoxic
brain injury indicate low likelihood of full neurological recovery.  These findings were conveyed to
the neurology consult team and to the primary team at the time of the recording.  Patient will be
placed on a long-term EEG monitoring

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This 36-year-old woman with neurofibromatosis, status post recurrent neurofibroma in lower extremity, patient presented 12/11/2014 with respiratory arrest and collapse of the right lung with coma followed by seizure.
MEDICATIONS:  Vancomycin, Lasix, Celexa, baclofen, diazepam, opioids.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient was intubated, comatose with occasional whole body jerks, maximum with the abdominal muscles.  Impedances were generally under 5 kilohms, but not exclusively so.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG demonstrates a burst suppression pattern with periods of suppression lasting as long as 9 seconds, but more typically 3-4 seconds in duration.  Bursts of high amplitude activity were noted typically under 1 second in duration was a high amplitude myoclonic spike, essentially obscured by muscle artifact and then some brief beta or mixed frequency activity.  Most bursts were isolated discharges, but some occurred with pairs.
Tactile stimulation of the patient did not activate the record.
Over the course of the record, the EEG pattern was relatively stable.
Heart rate 95 BMP.
IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to,
Acute burst suppression pattern for this individual recorded approximately 7-9 hours after cardiac arrest.
Absence of reactivity and/or variability.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings were discussed with the clinical team including the gravity of this hyperacute pattern.  This patient will go on to long-term EEG monitoring.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to,
Acute burst suppression pattern for this individual recorded approximately 7-9 hours after cardiac arrest. Absence of reactivity and/or variability.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 69-year-old left handed woman with hypothyroidism, depression, weight loss, and rapidly progressive memory loss.
MEDICATIONS:  Remeron, Synthroid, Ritalin, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is slow and disorganized with excess background theta.  There is a glimpse of a 7 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.  There are bursts of rhythmic frontal delta as well as bursts of shifting arrhythmic delta activity.  There is a slight underlying asymmetry with a bit more arrhythmic delta activity on the left in comparison to the right.
Heart rate: 60-90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due,
Background slowing and disorganization with a sharply contoured  background.
Prominent shifting, slowing.
FIRDA.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No definitive epileptiform features were noted in this record.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not obtained, nor was sleep.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a follow up study capturing sleep is suggested.  A repeat study may also be of value to assess progression of this syndrome.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due,
Background slowing and disorganization with a sharply contoured  background. Prominent shifting, slowing. FIRDA.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 33-year-old woman with 6-month history of epilepsy.  Seizure-free for the last 2 months.  Seizures occur with abrupt loss of consciousness, shaking, postictal confusion.  Past history of bipolar disease, alcohol, and drug abuse.
MEDICATIONS:  unknown
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 10.5 hertz, 30 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements with an increase in theta.  Head rocking artifact was noted in drowsiness, hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background.  Photic stimulation did elicit a driving response.
Heart rate 50 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness with bradycardia.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.  If additional information is needed, a more prolonged study capturing deeper stages of sleep is suggested.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness with bradycardia.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 52-year-old woman, status post aortic dissection repair on Sunday, 03/08/2015, for emergent dissection.  Subsequently found to have a massive right hemiparesis with smaller strokes on the left.  Intubated, but responsive.
MEDICATIONS:  Morphine, nicardipine, Lasix, fentanyl, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed at bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system with one channel EKG.  The patient is intubated, but responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Background EEG is markedly abnormal, but demonstrates a continuous pattern.  The overall pattern is relatively suppressed from the right hemisphere with smaller amounts of alpha and theta frequency activity.  From the left hemisphere, arrhythmic delta activity was noted with occasional sharp waves noted in the left hemisphere including left mid temporal or central regions.  These are medium amplitude sharp waves.  There is also a small amount of wicket noted from the left.  This record does capture some drowsiness with an increase in beta frequency activity.  When the patient is more active, there is a bit more muscle noted.
Heart rate:  98 BPM to 112 BPM, faster heart rate when the patient is a little bit more active.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due:
Generalized background slowing.
An asymmetry with significant disruption of faster frequency activity on the right.
Intermittent attenuations noted, which are asymmetric, more remarkable from the right.
Occasional sharp waves noted from the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function affecting both gray and white matter, but more significantly involving the right hemisphere with more significant disruption of activity from the right.  The sharp waves are relatively blunted in nature, but in this individual with bihemispheric stroke, raise some potential for seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due Generalized background slowing. An asymmetry with significant disruption of faster frequency activity on the right. Intermittent attenuations noted, which are asymmetric, more remarkable from the right. Occasional sharp waves noted from the left.

report:
﻿History:	31 year old woman who had several seizures in 5/2014.  Large left frontal
meningioma was subsequently found and patient underwent tumor resection.  She
has occasional seizures since then.
Medications:	Tegretol
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 11Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse excess beta activity is present.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha
rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves appear diffusely, followed by a few vertex waves.  Vertex
waves are more pronounced over the left.
Occasional polymorphic delta activity is noted over the left frontotemporal region.  Additional,
moderate amplitude fast activity is present over the bilateral frontocentral regions (breach artifact),
left>right.  A single left frontotemporal sharp transient is captured.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with fair cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at
multiple flash rates.  A single EKG lead demonstrates heart rate <60 bpm.
Summary of Findings:
No stage 2 sleep
Breach artifact, bilateral, frontocentral
Beta, excessive
Sharp transients, one, left frontotemporal
Focal slowing, polymorphic, occasional, moderate, left frontotemporal
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL awake and drowsy 28 minute EEG due to occasional moderate left
frontotemporal focal slowing.  This finding is indicative of focal cerebral dysfunction, which is
etiologically non-specific, but possibly structural in origin.  Breach artifact is secondary to the
underlying skull defect.  The presence of a single left frontotemporal sharp transient waveform is of
uncertain clinical significance.  It occurs in the same location as breach artifact and focal slowing.
The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of
epilepsy.  Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL awake and drowsy 28 minute EEG due to occasional moderate left
frontotemporal focal slowing.  This finding is indicative of focal cerebral dysfunction, which is
etiologically non-specific, but possibly structural in origin.  Breach artifact is secondary to the
underlying skull defect.  The presence of a single left frontotemporal sharp transient waveform is of
uncertain clinical significance.  It occurs in the same location as breach artifact and focal slowing

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 22-year-old woman with near syncopal spell on 04/11/2015.  The patient experienced an episode of shaking all over with questionable loss of consciousness, blurry vision, and 25 minutes of tingling throughout her body.
MEDICATIONS:  Naprosyn
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  This is a technically satisfactory EEG with most impedances below 5 kilohms with the exception of the T1 and T2 electrodes.  This EEG captures wakefulness and brief sleep.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is an 11.7 Hz alpha rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  The overall background is appropriately organized for age.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in beta followed by rhythmic theta, but without sustained stage II sleep.
Photic stimulation elicited a bilateral driving response.  Hyperventilation did not significantly activate the record.
Heart rate:  72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in awake through brief stage 1 sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG, does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy and if seizures are a strong concern, a more prolonged study capturing deeper stages of sleep is suggested.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in awake through brief stage 1 sleep.

report:
History:	60 year old woman with unexplained frequent fall during which she remains awake.
Medications:	LAMICTAL, TOPAMAX, ABILIFY, ZOLOFT, ATIVAN, ATARAX
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 11Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Fast alpha variant is present.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity
is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows to
central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm
attenuates and becomes intermittent.  During brief stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to
moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with fair cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving
at multiple flash rates.  Occasional 50-75uV, 100 msec positive sharp transients occur bilaterally
over the occipital regions during saccadic eye movements with the eyes open.
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
Alpha variant, fast
Sleep, stage 2, very brief
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 29-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and very briefly asleep. The lack of epileptiform
discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 29-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and very briefly asleep. The lack of epileptiform
discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 38-year-old man with childhood head trauma and development of epilepsy as an young adult. 5 year history of  Complex partial seizures followed by tonic-clonic seizures 5 years ago.  Current seizure frequency, unknown, intermittent dizziness.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This was a technically acceptable EEG with impedances below 5 kilohms with the exception of the T1-T2 electrodes.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, the EEG is well organized.  There is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  Somewhat irregular mixed theta delta was noted in the frontal central regions. It is present bilaterally, but is somewhat more prominent in the right hemisphere.
Hyperventilation was performed early on in the record and very quickly produces a feeling in the patient of dizziness and jitteriness.  Bursts of frontal theta are noted, somewhat irregular and a little bit more prominent on the right in hyperventilation.  Photic stimulation was performed immediately after hyperventilation, in the early parts of the record and did elicit a driving response.  The patient remained quite anxious and there is a great deal of muscle artifact noted in the background.  In this challenging EEG with a great deal of muscle artifact, there appears to be an underlying 4 hertz spike and wave complex, typically seen in the right hemisphere sometimes with a bihemispheric predominance.  Review of the video identifies no twitching of the patient during the discharges.
Heart rate:  66 bpm.  Frequent PVCs.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Intermittent rhythmic somewhat irregular theta delta noted in relaxed wakefulness, and somewhat accentuated by hyperventilation.
In this technically challenging EEG, likely an underlying spike and wave complex seen a bit more prominently in the right hemisphere, but sometimes of bilateral representation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  In comparison to a previous study 5 years ago, the patient had 3-5 hertz frontally predominant spike and wave activity as well as right frontal spike and wave activity and right
focal slowing.  Because of the degree of muscle artifact, these findings are not as well identified.  Additional evaluation of the patient regarding the tremulousness and PVCs may be of value.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to Intermittent rhythmic somewhat irregular theta delta noted in relaxed wakefulness, and somewhat accentuated by hyperventilation. In this technically challenging EEG, likely an underlying spike and wave complex seen a bit more prominently in the right hemisphere, but sometimes of bilateral representation.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  An 89-year-old woman with right intracerebral hemorrhage, confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  A 23 minute digital video EEG was performed at bedside in ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  This was a technically challenging record in a confused patient, but it is technically acceptable.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In apparent wakefulness, the background EEG is diffusely slow with a theta pattern and a glimpse of a 5 Hz alpha rhythm.  There is a subtle asymmetry noted with a bit of underlying arrhythmic delta activity in the right hemisphere including central parietal region and subtle disruption of the more rhythmic theta.  There are subtle right temporal sharp waves noted, maximum at T4.
Heart rate:  Irregular, 78 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to;
Generalized background slowing.
Subtle focal slowing ipsilateral to the hemorrhage.
Handful of subtle underlying sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No seizures were recorded.  These findings are congruent with the clinical scenario.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to;
Generalized background slowing. Subtle focal slowing ipsilateral to the hemorrhage. Handful of subtle underlying sharp waves.

HISTORY :

SEDATION : propofol noted to be off at study start
TECHNIQUE:_
A 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20 system with Tl/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record and included a single channel of EKG.
EEG BACKGROUND:
The record opens to a nearly continuous mixture of disorganized alpha, beta, and theta frequencies that alternate with periods of attenuation < 3 seconds.	There are no definite sleep transients.
During stimulation, the background reacts, changing to a continuous mixture of disorganized delta, alpha, and theta frequencies. There is no posterior dominant rhythm.
There is moderate generalized slowing. There is no focal slowing.
EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:
None
OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):
None
ACTIVATION PROCEDURES: Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.
HEART RATE:
A heart rate of 66 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.
IMPRESSION:
This is an abnormal awake and asleep routine EEG due to:
1. Moderate background slowing and disorganization
CLINICAL CORRELATION:
These findings indicate the presence of moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which may in part be explained by medication effect.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION This is an abnormal awake and asleep routine EEG due to 1. Moderate background slowing and disorganization

report:
History:	48 year old woman who presents with fainting episodes.
Medications:	None
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse excess beta activity is present.  During drowsiness, the background
slows to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm
attenuates and becomes intermittent.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate
voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces mild diffuse
symmetric background slowing.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates.  A single EKG lead demonstrates regular
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
Sleep, stage 2
Beta, excessive
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. Excessive beta activity could be secondary to
the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. Excessive beta activity could be secondary to
the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 60-year-old male found down on


December 14th with traumatic intracerebral hemorrhage, skull

fracture, went on to have right craniotomy.  Left frontal EVD.

Now, with right upper gaze deviation.



MEDICATIONS:  Keppra. No others listed.



INTRODUCTION:  Twenty four minute digital video EEG was performed

at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement

with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient was intubated, but was


examined during the EEG.  There was no record of the use of

sedative, hypnotic medications in the report provided by the

technologist.



DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG demonstrates a medium

amplitude pattern with a mixed frequency pattern.  There are


lower voltage theta and delta frequency activity.  Intermittent,




subtle attenuations were noted, with attenuation or at least a

decrease in amplitude of the background.  These effects last 1 to


3 seconds and are not entirely a burst suppression pattern.  In

the sections of the record with more vigorous cerebral activity,


there is right frontal delta.  There is also a lower voltage

right frontal fast wave or lower voltage frontal sharp wave noted

intermittently.  Rare left frontal sharp waves were also noted.

Tactile stimulation of the patient seem to produce an attenuation


of cerebral activity lasting 7 seconds in duration.



Heart rate 144 bpm.


IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:

1. A low voltage slow pattern.


2. Intermittent attenuation of the background.

3. The phenomenon of attenuation of the background with tactile


stimulation.

4. Intermittent sharp waves noted from either frontal region,

right greater than left.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No seizures were recorded.  The

epileptiform features noted were in the region of the previous


cranial defect and may have been accentuated by that fact.  In

the absence of the use of sedative, hypnotic medications, the

background described above is a worrisome pattern.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to 
1. A low voltage slow pattern. 

2. Intermittent attenuation of the background. 
3. The phenomenon of attenuation of the background with tactile


stimulation. 
4. Intermittent sharp waves noted from either frontal region,

right greater than left.

TECHNIQUE:


A 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the




International 10-20 system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a

NicOne system. This was a  technically satisfactory record and


included a single channel of EKG HV, and photic stimulation. The

patient was restless.



EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is somewhat poorly organized but relatively

symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and


generous of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal

anterior-to-posterior gradient.  Wakefulness is characterized by


a symmetric and reactive 11 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm

(PDR), which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.

At times the alpha is higher amplitude on the left, and there are

lambda waves.



During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and


fragmentation of the posterior dominant rhythm, and diffuse

background slowing are seen.




Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with

synchronous and symmetric vertex waves, sleep spindles and


K-complexes. Slow wave sleep was not captured.  POSTS are

asymmetric, more notable on the left


Focal slowing is present: See HV below. In addition, in stage I


sleep there is left occipital 4 Hz activity



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

No epileptiform activity is present.


OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):


None



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: elicits bilateral slowing but more

sustained 4 Hz activity, Left temporal maximum



Photic Stimulation: elicits bilateral driving



EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during

this study.



HEART RATE:


A heart rate of 54 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.


IMPRESSION:

This is abnormal  routine EEG.


1. Poorly organized background

2. Mild excess theta


3. Mild excess beta

4. Subtle focal features in the left hemisphere.


CLINICAL CORRELATION:


This awake and asleep routine EEG supports a diffuse CNS process.

Medications may play a role. Subtle focal features may be


correlated with imaging. .

1. Poorly organized background

2. Mild excess theta

report:
HISTORY:

58 y.o. female with a history of skull or other tumor, s/p craniotomy.  Recent OR
for drainage of fluid and treatment of hydrocephalus. Evaluate for left facial twitch.  S/p trach, not
very interactive.  Referred for routine EEG for characterization of seizures.




MEDICATIONS:

Not reported



SEDATION: not reported.



TECHNIQUE:

A bedside  ICU Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the
International 10-20 system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a
technically satisfactory record and included a single channel of EKG and  Verbal stimulation.  The
patient has a bone flap.




EEG BACKGROUND:




The waking background is abnormal.  The patient is awake, with eye opening and on the left there is
an organized  mixture of theta  alpha and beta frequencies, with a symmetric and reactive 7-9 Hertz
posterior dominant rhythm (PDR). The normal anterior-to-posterior gradient of frequency and
amplitude is present.



The right hemisphere demonstrates marked reduction in faster frequency with more of a delta/theta
featureless pattern.  Superimposed on this is R frontocentral breech with higher amplitude R F4-C4
delta activity and focal sharp waves F4 maximum.  There is intermittent beta accentuation in the
region of the breach.




There is muscle twitch artifact noted on the left, seen at times diffusely from left temporal scalp
electrodes and intermittently as a focal twitch. The isolated twitches lack consistent link to the R
frontal sharps.




Right  focal slowing is present.


EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:


See above


OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):


None


ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:


Auditory and tactile stimulation do not activate the records


EVENTS:


Focal facial twitch without consistent EEG correlate


HEART RATE:


A heart rate of 100 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.


IMPRESSION:


This is an abnormal ICU routine EEG due to:

1. Continuous R focal slowing.

2. In the context of R sided breech rhythm, R frontal focal slowing and intermittent sharp waves


CLINICAL CORRELATION:


These findings must be interpreted in the clinical context of the patient's motor activity and imaging.
While no electrographic seizures were defined by this study, the possibility of epilepsy partialis is not
excluded by this study.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 

This is an abnormal ICU routine EEG due to 
1. Continuous R focal slowing. 
2. In the context of R sided breech rhythm, R frontal focal slowing and intermittent sharp waves

system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG, hyperventilation, and photic stimulation.




EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is characterized by the presence of fairly generalized poorly organized
medium amplitude 5-6 Hz activity with intermixed irregular delta frequency slowing and
superimposed muscle artifact. Occasional runs of medium to high amplitude irregular delta activity
and anteriorly predominant triphasiform discharges were seen during periods of increased drowsiness.
Occasional sharp-and slow-wave discharges were seen in the right frontotemporal region at T4-F8
and infrequent low amplitude sharp transients were also seen at P3.





Sleep is not captured



No focal slowing is present.



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None

no effect.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce
any EEG changes.

This is an abnormal awake and drowsy 1 hour EEG due to:

1. Diffuse background slowing and disorganization

2. Occasional runs of triphasiform activity during drowsiness.


3. Right frontotemporal sharp-slow wave discharges at T4-F8.

4. Infrequent low amplitude sharp transients in the left parietal region at P3.




CLINICAL CORRELATION:



The diffuse background slowing and triphasic activity are nonspecific and indicates a moderate
bihemispheric functional disturbance such as asking variety of metabolic or other generalized
encephalopathies of various etiologies. Focal interictal sharp activity indicates a potential
epileptogenic region in the right anterior temporal area at T4-F8, with questionable minimal
irritative activity also seen infrequently in the left parietal region at P3.

alpha and beta frequencies, with a symmetric and reactive 10 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm

Most of the study consists of drowsiness.  During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation
and fragmentation of the posterior dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.




Sleep is not captured


No generalized slowing is present.


Rare left temporal polymorphic slowing is present.

Frequent (>1/min to <1/10s) bilateral synchronous and independent (left > right) anterior to mid

None

Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is performed for 180 seconds with good cooperation and produces

These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicators of left temporal cerebral dysfunction.

Sharply contoured theta waves noted over the bitemporal regions synchronously and independently

The waking background is characterized by the presence of a medium voltage 9-10 Hertz posterior

This is an abnormal awake and drowsy  routine EEG due to:


1. Continuous irregular right central and temporal slowing.

2. Infrequent sharp transients in the right temporal region at T4.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:





These findings indicate the presence of a right hemispheric functional disturbance with mild irritative
features in the mid right temporal region.

1. Continuous irregular right central and temporal slowing.
